              <article class='text-to-speech__section'>
                <h3 id="section_4.1.5" class="heading-small">4.1.5 Levelling devices</h3>
                <p>Make sure any manual headlamp levelling devices (driver controls) work by:</p>
                <ul class="list-bullet">
                  <li>switching on the dipped beam headlamps</li>
                  <li>operating the manual levelling device</li>
                  <li>checking that the headlamp beams move up and down </li>
                  <li>returning the levelling device control to its original position</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Vehicles with high intensity discharge
                  <span class="bold"> </span>(HID) or LED dipped beam headlamps may be fitted with a suspension or headlamp self-levelling system. If these systems
                  have been fitted, they must work. </p>
                <p>Sometimes it isn't easy to determine if the self-levelling systems work. In such cases you should give the benefit of the
                  doubt.</p>
                <p>You can identify HID headlamps from:</p>
                <ul class="list-bullet">
                  <li>‘DCR’ mark on the headlamp lens or body</li>
                  <li>an igniter module or inverter behind the headlamp </li>
                  <li>taking a few seconds to reach full intensity</li>
                  <li>a bluish tinge to the light</li>
                </ul>
                <p>HID headlamps use high voltage. You should take care when inspecting these headlamps.</p>
